[{'node': {'text': "DTL9 is Botanic Gardens Station!
.

.

All of us know that Botanic Gardens MRT is named after the park that is right by the station. It's a long walk through the park, so drop by the restroom before enjoying your hike!
.

-
It looks different from the rest because of its red tiled walls and black marble counters at the sink area. Buuuut... Bugis MRT restrooms are not that great, in fact in ranks the lowest in terms of overall usability. The flushing in this cubicle is faulty. And the restroom doesn't rate high on cleanliness too. Not to mention the odour. üòì
-
It is probably because Bugis DTL restroom is one of the most used on the DTL, resulting in its poor state. However, I actually had to come back to this restroom because the 1st time I was there, it was being cleaned. So I came back after they were done (30 mins later), but the restroom didn't look like it was cleaned. I'm not blaming the cleaners, there was probably so little they could do due to the high traffic.

[{'node': {'text': "DTL12 is Little India MRT station!
-
The cubicles in this restroom are especially spacious, like the toilet bowl is further to the stall door, as compared to the other restrooms I have visited. I believe it's just the way that the restroom is built and located, but it peaked my interest to notice this difference, anyway! üòÖ As you can see in the photos, DTL restrooms got themselves another clean and efficient toilet. They're doing very well. üòè
-
What do you do when the effects of the curry you just ate at one of the many eateries in Little India kicks in and your stomach starts to give you warnings when you're shopping the streets? Of course the answer is to rush to the nearest toilet. And if the nearest to you happens to be the MRT restrooms, at least you can be assured that the toilet is clean and ready for you to use in comfort!!
-
I give the Little India DTL restrooms üöΩüöΩüöΩüöΩ ! -

[{'node': {'text': "DTL10 is Stevens MRT station!
.
Similar to Botanic Gardens station, Stevens MRT Station also has mint green stall walls. What I really like about the cubicles though, is that they're unusually spacious... Another clean and completely equipped toilet! The restrooms in this area of the DTL are just really good, aren't they?
.
When you tap in and tap out of an MRT Station, you still get charged for it even if you only spend 5 minutes at the platform. That's unfair, especially if you simply made a mistake, right? Well, because too many people were making that mistake at Stevens MRT, LTA gave commuters a 10-minute grace period to tap out if they've made a mistake. Stevens MRT is the only MRT station that gives that grace period. So if you happen to be waiting at the MRT platform for the train and you feel a sudden need to use the toilet (as plenty of IBS sufferers feel, by the way!) good news! You won't be charged for tapping out. ‚ò∫Ô∏è
.
